    {
      "title": "Rules for Syllable Division",
      "subtopics": [
        {
          "title": "Dividing Words into Syllables",
          "sections": [
            {
              "text": "Knowing how to divide words into syllables helps with reading and pronunciation. Here are some simple rules:",
              "examples": [
                {
                  "label": "Rule 1: Compound Words",
                  "value": "Divide between the two smaller words. Example: sun-set, black-board, tooth-brush, class-room."
                },
                {
                  "label": "Rule 2: Two Consonants Between Vowels",
                  "value": "If there are two different consonants between two vowels, divide between the consonants. Example: gar-den, sis-ter, bas-ket, doc-tor, com-mon."
                },
                {
                  "label": "Rule 3: One Consonant Between Vowels",
                  "value": "If there is one consonant between two vowels, the consonant usually goes with the second vowel (making an open syllable). Example: ho-tel, pa-per, ti-ger, o-pen, mu-sic."
                },
                {
                  "label": "Rule 4: 'le' at the End",
                  "value": "If a word ends with '-le' and has a consonant before it, that consonant often goes with '-le'. Example: ta-ble, ap-ple, lit-tle, can-dle, pur-ple."
                },
                {
                  "label": "Rule 5: Prefixes and Suffixes",
                  "value": "Divide between a base word and its prefix (start of a word) or suffix (end of a word). Example: un-happy, read-ing, farm-er, re-play, teach-er."
                }
              ],
              "usage_examples": [
                "The 'sun-set' is beautiful.",
                "My 'sis-ter' is kind.",
                "We stayed in a 'ho-tel'.",
                "This is a big 'ta-ble'.",
                "He is 'un-hap-py' today.",
                "I am 'read-ing' a book.",
                "The 'farm-er' is busy.",
                "Please 're-play' the song.",
                "Our 'teach-er' is good."
              ],
              "media": {
